          "Notice that Paul defines agape almost entirely by behavior, not feeling. Patient. Kind. Not arrogant. Not irritable. Keeps no record. You can do every one of these whether or not you feel loving in the moment. That is the freedom of it. Love is not waiting for a feeling. It is a set of choices you make toward the person in front of you.",
          "Two of these land especially hard in marriage. Makrothymei, long-tempered, a long fuse. Marriage is where your short fuse shows up most, the snapping at the end of the day, the irritation over small things. Love stretches the fuse out. And ou logizetai, keeps no record of wrongs, an accounting word. Love refuses to keep the ledger you keep pulling out in fights. That ledger has to die.",
          "Then the four alls at the end. Bears all things, believes all things, hopes all things, endures all things. This is covenant love going the distance. It does not bail when things get hard. It keeps believing the best, keeps hoping, keeps carrying the weight, keeps enduring. This is the love that stays, defined in detail.",
