          "Weaker vessel, skeuos, is not an insult. It is a charge to the stronger one. The image is a treasured heirloom, the kind of thing you handle with extra care precisely because it is precious. Peter is telling husbands, you may be physically stronger, you may hold cultural power, so use it the way you would handle something valuable and breakable. Gently. Carefully. Protectively. Strength exists to shield, not to bully.",
          "And then immediately, coheir, sygkleronomos, the same word for being a joint-heir with Christ Himself. Before God, she is not lesser. She inherits everything you inherit, the same grace, the same glory. So whatever differences exist in role, they sit on top of total equality in worth. A husband who forgets that has forgotten the gospel.",
