          "Notice what Paul warns husbands about: pikraino, do not be bitter, do not be harsh. Stop being sharp. It is telling. With all the authority a man held in that world, Paul's concern was not that he would be too gentle. It was that he would curdle into harshness, sarcasm, a hard and bitter edge. Men, that is the warning with your name on it. The drift is toward harshness, and you have to actively fight it.",
          "Then Titus shows the other half. Younger women had to be taught philandrous, to love their husbands, and philoteknous, to love their children. Sit with that. Even love for your own family is not automatic. It has to be cultivated, taught, modeled, chosen. The warmth in a home does not happen by accident. Someone decides to build it, day after day.",
